Commentary.Commentary: We are back for South Africa's first innings reply! The umpires and the Indian players are out in the middle. It will be the stand-in skipper Dean Elgar to open the innings alongside Aiden Markram for the Proteas. Jasprit Bumrah has the new ball in hand and is raring to go. Three slips in place, let's go...
... SECOND INNINGS ...

Right then, conditions are still pretty overcast and India have a bit of a momentum boost courtesy of KL Rahul and the tail. The onus is now on the Proteas openers to come out and show their grit and determination against the new ball and a fired up Indian pace attack. Join us in a bit as the South African first innings is up next.

South Africa have finally been able to knock over the last two wickets but it has taken them 8.4 overs from the start of Day 2 and has cost them a further 37 runs. The first innings for mostly a tale of two individual players on either side who stepped up their game and did the job for their country. For the Proteas, it was Kagiso Rabada who ripped through the Indian top and middle order ending up with a well-deserved five-wicket haul. For India, it was the centurion in Centurion, KL Rahul who became the first overseas batter to score two Test tons at this ground. His stand with the likes of Shardul Thakur and Mohammed Siraj early on Day 2 has really taken India to a score with which they will be pleased with. Nandre Burger was one of the other standouts as he ended with three vital wickets on his Test debut.

OUT! TIMBER! RIGHT THROUGH HIS DEFENCE! Nandre Burger finishes things up as he cleans up KL Rahul and India have been bundled out for 245 runs. Burger steams in from around the stumps and serves it on a fullish length, angling it in from the off stump. Rahul looks to flick but leaves a huge gap between bat and pad and the ball just beats the inside edge to crash into the stumps. End of a fine, fine inning from Rahul.

Commentary.Commentary: We are set for the start of the play on Day 2! The umpires make their way out to the middle followed by the players of South Africa. KL Rahul and Mohammed Siraj also stride out to resume their overnight stay on the crease. It will be Gerald Coetzee (12-1-53-0) to begin proceedings with the ball on Day 2. Let's play...

UPDATE 1.43 pm IST (8.13 am GMT) - The visuals from the ground show that the light drizzle has subsided and the covers are completely coming off. We should get an official word regarding the start of play soon. The groundsmen are working around the clock to get the outfield fit for the start of play. Stay tuned for more on this. Great news as there is an official start time - 1.55 pm IST (8.25 am GMT) which is just a few minutes away. Do join us in a bit for live action.

Meanwhile, the star of the show for South Africa on Day 1, Kagiso Rabada is down for a quick chat. He says he tried to get the ball in decent areas and tried to stick to the basics and not try something extra. There was unarguably a good purchase off the deck throughout the day which helped them a lot. Adds that Virat Kohli was going pretty well and he was dropped but it didn't cost them too much as he was dismissed sooner. Adds that the target would be to get the two remaining wickets as early as possible. Further says that it was a comprehensive performance overall. He then appreciates Nandre Burger and says that it was a dream debut for him as he bowled in the right areas and picked up some crucial wickets and hopes that he continues to do so in the future.

UPDATE 1.26 pm IST (7.56 am GMT) - It is official, the start of play on Day 2 has been officially delayed due to a wet outfield. It doesn't look to be a long delay though as the drizzle is very light and the main concern is the outfield. Stay tuned for more updates.

UPDATE 1.10 pm IST (7.40 am GMT) - Just 20 minutes or so away from the start of action on Day 2 and the covers come on due to a drizzle. It was pretty light for some time and the pitch was left uncovered but now the covers do come on and we might have a delayed start. Stick around for more updates. Minutes later, the two umpires walk out with folded umbrellas and have a look at the ground conditions which indicates that it was just a passing shower and we might not have too much of a delay.

The live visuals from the ground show that there is no rain but it is a fairly cloudy morning in Centurion. For now, the first session on Day 2 is all set to start on schedule at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT). It could be a make-or-break day for both sides which is generally Day 3 but with the game moving along at a brisk pace, Day 2 could be the one that makes the telling difference. Stay tuned for further updates.

India on the other hand would have wanted to play out Day 1 rather than walk back just when KL Rahul was at his best. The Indian wicket-keeper is unbeaten on 70 vital runs and just has a couple of batters remaining to aid him and he will look to pick up some more runs early on Day 2. Apart from Rahul though, there were a few more gritty innings that didn't end up being big knocks but Virat Kohli, Shreyas Iyer and Shardul Thakur made handy runs. Anything around the 250-run mark and the visitors will be delighted with the bowling attack they have.

The home side, South Africa had a field day with the ball in hand, well for most of the day anyway as Kagiso Rabada weaved magic with the red cherry in hand and picked up a sublime five-wicket haul. Apart from him, Test debutant Nandre Burger impressed as well with a couple of big strikes but the two remaining pacers were pretty sub-par. Marco Jansen in particular had no rhythm at all and with skipper Temba Bavuma getting injured in the field, the Proteas have some work to do coming into Day 2. They looked quite tired in the final session and would have been pleased to see the covers come on when KL Rahul and the tailenders were punishing them for some sloppy bowling

Hello and welcome to Day 2 of the 1st Test between South Africa and India at the SuperSport Park in Centurion. Day 1 saw us witness quite an enthralling battle between bat and ball for two full sessions but with just 9 overs into the final session of the day, the Rain Gods smiled and play had to be abandoned. Let's hope for a much brighter day, filled with cricketing action. Given that only 59 overs were possible on Day 1, we will have 98 overs for each of the remaining four days which given how the game has progressed may not even be required unless the weather plays spoilsport.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, Day 1 of the first Test between South Africa and India has been full of ups and downs but weather has had the final say. Given the nature of the pitch, the weather might not eventually go on to play spoilsport but it will certainly make things even more interesting. India are 208/8 and will be looking to put on some crucial runs on board early on Day 2. It will be interesting to see whether Kagiso Rabada and co. are able to wind up proceedings in the first hour or not. The official start time on Day 2 (Wednesday) is at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT) but looking at the overs lost, we could have an early start, usually, 30 minutes early. There is no official confirmation though. Cheers!

The 'Boxing Day' Test at SuperSport Park in Centurion got off to an ominous start as the toss was delayed but that wasn't a long delay as play got underway and India were put into bat. Kagiso Rabada started right on the money and picked up the prized wicket of the Indian skipper Rohit Sharma after which the Test debutant Nandre Burger picked up two further wickets to put the hosts in command. There were a couple of dropped catches and an injury to the Proteas skipper Temba Bavuma in the first session after which Virat Kohli and Shreyas Iyer built up a steady stand. Right after the Lunch break though, Rabada ripped through the middle order and had India in heaps of trouble. Shardul Thakur and KL Rahul fought back well but Rabada ended with a five-fer and along with that surpassed 500 International wickets. India came into the final session, 7 wickets down for 176 runs but Rahul stepped on the gas and has picked up vital runs for his side and is unbeaten on 70 runs as well. Apart from Rabada and Burger, South Africa haven't quite troubled the batters.

UPDATE 8.18 pm IST (2.48 pm GMT) - There it is, we have official word and play has been called off on Day 1! The rain is persistent and the outfield had taken a lot of water before play began and there are some wet patches and with the light fading, there was no other option to call play off early.

UPDATE 8.10 pm IST (2.40 pm GMT) - It is still raining in Centurion and that too pretty heavily it seems. Given the rain and the fading light, we might not see a restart on Day 1 but lets hope for the best as there's still some time left in the day and the weather can change pretty quickly. Stick around for more updates.

Oh, no! The players are going off! There is a bit of rain around and the umpires have taken the call of aborting play for now as the light seems to be pretty low as well. Out come the covers and we are in for a bit of a delay. The umpires actually hung around for a bit and the covers didn't come on right away but now the rain seems to be picking up and the covers do come on. Stay tuned as we bring you further updates.

Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness for the final session on Day 1 of the first Test between South Africa and India. Out come the umpires and the players of South Africa to take their places on the field. KL Rahul and Jasprit Bumrah are set to resume their stay as well. Still no sign of the Proteas skipper Temba Bavuma as Dean Elgar continues to lead the side. Kagiso Rabada to resume his spell after the break. Let's play...
... DAY 1, SESSION 3 ...

Right then, one more session to go on Day 1 and it could prove to be a vital one. Will India come back and showcase a counterattack? or will the Proteas continue to dominate and pull the curtains on the Indian innings? Stay tuned as we come back shortly for the post-Tea session which commences at 7 pm IST (1.30 pm GMT).

South Africa on the other end will be mighty pleased with their bowling performance that made India work hard for every run. The consistency with lines and lengths proved pivotal in dismantling the strong Indian batting line-up. Kagiso Rabada was the pick of the bowlers for his five-fer that included some big fishes of the Indian team and got all four wickets in the session gone by. A great debut performance by Nandre Burger who claimed 2 wickets in the first session but couldn't do much in this session. Gerald Coetzee and Marco Jansen have bowled well in patches but neither of them has looked like taking a wicket which is a slight worry for the hosts.

Session Summary - 24 overs, 85 runs and 4 wickets! That's the end of the session and the players head to Tea after what has been a fiery and dominant performance by the Proteas who put India on the backfoot right from the word go, post Lunch. The partnership between Virat Kohli and Shreyas Iyer was crucial and flourished well after 3 early wickets for India. Kagiso Rabada broke the shackles and knocked off both the set batters within the first hour of play in the session. KL Rahul and Shardul Thakur knocked a counter punch and took the attack to the Proteas bowlers scoring at a healthy rate. Shardul Thakur showcased his grit and determination after being bumped multiple times by the South African pacers. The wickets kept falling at regular intervals and no batter could maximise the starts they had got. KL Rahul looks promising and in good touch for his 39 off 71 balls so far but will need support from the other end to take it deep post Tea.
Good length on off, angling in, KL Rahul hangs back and just dabs it down around the corner for a single. That will be Tea on Day 1!

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Kagiso Rabada with his fourth wicket and what a stellar spell he is having. Rabada bowls this one a touch short at 133 clicks around off, angling it in and the ball bounces a shade extra. Ravichandran Ashwin looks to block off the front foot but the extra bounce means the ball takes the shoulder of the bat and flies away toward third slip where the substitute fielder, Wiaan Mulder times his jump well and grabs it with both hands. The replays show that it flew off the gloves. South Africa are firmly in control now. Kagiso Rabada is a bit like Stuart Broad, at times he will look very ordinary but once he gets into his groove, and finds his rhythm, he has the potential to run through any batting order in a jiffy.

Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the post-Lunch on Day 1! The umpires and the players of South Africa make their way back out to the middle. Virat Kohli and Shreyas Iyer are also out to resume their innings. There's no news on the injury status of Temba Bavuma as we aren't sure if he has taken the field or not. It will be Kagiso Rabada (7-2-15-1) to resume proceedings with the ball after the break.
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

The Proteas would be very happy with the way they bowled for the majority in this first session. India, on the other hand, struggled early on but Virat Kohli and Shreyas Iyer have resisted pretty well against the lethal South African pace battery. Will the Indians continue to weave a good partnership or will the Proteas keep the wickets falling? Too many questions looming. Stay tuned for the post-lunch session which will begin at 4.40 pm IST (11.10 am GMT).

South Africa on the other hand, had a perfect initiation to this Boxing Day Test match as Kagiso Rabada didn't take too long to draw first blood by dismissing the Indian skipper Rohit Sharma on a paltry score of 5 runs. Rabada looked fairly threatening with the movement off the deck and bowled right on the money. The Proteas bowlers asked tough questions to the Indian batters upfront. Nandre Burger, the debutant didn't miss the party as he chipped in with a couple of wickets by getting rid of Yashasvi Jaiswal and Shubman Gill on cheap scores. South Africans bowled with precision but they were a bit sloppy in the field as they dropped a couple of catches which, could've further dented the hopes of the visitors but now the hosts have to come back and start well in the next session against two set batters.

The players head to Lunch on Day 1 and what a riveting session of play we have had! India was invited to bat by the hosts after a delayed toss due to a wet field of play and seemingly overcast conditions. India had an ordinary start as Rohit Sharma perished on a pull shot, the shot which has garnered him a lot of runs over the years, in the 5th over against the rhythmic Kagiso Rabada. Yashasvi Jaiswal adapted to the conditions pretty well and negotiated the swing alertly but he was sooner dismissed on a mere 17. Adding to the misery, Shubman Gill was the next man to fall. Indians were struggling as they lost 3 wickets on just 24. Virat Kohli and Shreyas Iyer steadied the Indian ship and weaved a solid comeback partnership of 67 runs on a track that was not easy to bat at all. Both of them are up and running in their 30s and have resisted well against the Proteas.

A good leave from Shreyas Iyer to end the over and the session as well. This is full and outside off, inviting the drive but shaping away as well. Iyer looks to prod and play at it but lets it through to the keeper. That will be Lunch on Day 1!

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks break! Well, that was a fast and furious first hour of the Test and South Africa will be delighted with the start the quicks have provided. Kagiso Rabada has been the standout and Test debutant Nandre Burger has hit his stride immediately. India are under the pump after losing three wickets, could have been four had Marco Jansen not dropped Shreyas in the previous over. The pitch is a testing one and the duo of Virat Kohli and Shreyas Iyer might look to counterattack with the sun coming out and the ball losing some of its seaming abilities.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Excellent review and Nandre Burger has two wickets to his name. Burger bowls this one a touch shorter on the leg stump, getting it to shape further down leg. Shubman Gill is caught on the crease and has to awkwardly fend it away, leaving his hands past his hips. The ball goes past the bat and is gobbled up by Kyle Verreynne behind the stumps. Half an appeal for caught behind but the umpire says no! A lot of discussion between the skipper and his players and eventually, Temba Bavuma does review it. The replays roll in and UltraEdge shows that the glove was involved and India slip further down now.

Commentary.Commentary: We are set for the 'Boxing Day' Test. The umpires are out in the middle and the players of South Africa can be seen in a huddle. Skipper, Rohit Sharma will open the innings alongside Yashasvi Jaiswal for India. Kagiso Rabada has the brand-new cherry in hand and is raring to go. Three slips in place, let's go...

Indian skipper Rohit Sharma says that it's good to be back in the whites and says that he wasn't so sure about what to do so it was a good toss to lose. Says that they are quite aware of the conditions. Adds that the boys did pretty well in the limited-overs. Says that every time they come here with high hopes to win the series and it's a good opportunity for them to face the challenge this time as well. Updates about the team they have got four seamers and a spinner. Informs that Prasidh Krishna is to make his debut and Ravichandran Ashwin is in the playing XI as Ravindra Jadeja is out due to a neck spasm.

Temba Bavuma, the captain of South Africa says they will bowl first. He says the pitch will have a lot of moisture with it being under covers for so long, so they would look to exploit that. He adds that Lungi Ngidi is the only one who hasn't recovered fully and misses out on this game. Also informs that Nandre Burger and David Bedingham will make their debut. He concludes by talking about the battle with India and how they will have to bring out their 'A' game against this tough Indian side.

India (Playing XI) - Rohit Sharma (C), Yashasvi Jaiswal, Shubman Gill, Virat Kohli, Shreyas Iyer, KL Rahul (WK), Ravichandran Ashwin, Shardul Thakur, Jasprit Bumrah, Mohammed Siraj, Prasidh Krishna (On debut).

South Africa (Playing XI) - Dean Elgar, Aiden Markram, Tony de Zorzi, Temba Bavuma (C), Keegan Petersen, David Bedingham (On debut), Kyle Verreynne (WK), Marco Jansen, Gerald Coetzee, Kagiso Rabada, Nandre Burger (On debut).
TOSS - Up goes the flip of the coin and it lands in favor of South Africa. Temba Bavuma has decided to BOWL first.

PITCH REPORT - Shaun Pollock and Ravi Shastri are down at the center for the pitch report. Shaun starts off by saying that there is a good covering of grass on the pitch and the team winning the toss might want to bat first, keeping in mind the variable bounce that makes batting harder as the game progresses. He adds that with the overcast conditions, South Africa would be thinking of going with an all-pace attack but the injury concerns will be a key, especially with Lungi Ngidi most likely to miss out. Ravi adds that there could be cracks generated on the pitch which can get the spinners into the game and India might look to play Ravindra Jadeja along with Shardul Thakur and Prasidh Krishna.

UPDATE1.33 pm IST (8.03 am GMT) - We have news from the ground as the umpires have an inspection and inform the two skippers that the toss will take place at 1.45 pm IST (8.15 am GMT) with play set to begin at 2 pm IST (8.30 am GMT). Also, we can see Prasidh Krishna being handed his Test cap which confirms that he will make his debut. Grab a cup of coffee as the action is about to get underway.

With about 10 minutes left for the inspection, the Indian head coach, Rahul Dravid is up for a quick chat. Dravid says they have come close a couple of times and have played well but in critical moments they have fallen short by a few runs. Adds that they bowled really well in the last series here and you need some luck involved as well with a lot of plays and misses but you need to ensure that you are putting the ball in the right areas and capitalizing with the bat which makes a big difference against a strong home side. Says that he hopes after the two weeks, it will end positively for them. On Prasidh Krishna, he says that he is an exciting prospect but he has been a bit unlucky with injuries and was unable to play first-class cricket much but hopes that he can do well and it is a lovely moment when they are able to hand out that debut cap.

UPDATE 12.47 pm IST (7.17 am GMT) - The toss has been officially delayed due to some wet areas on the ground. The umpires have scheduled an inspection at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT). There is no rain at the moment which is a big positive, so, let's hope we get an update soon. Stay tuned.

India on the other hand have a very strong squad of players to choose from and their main dilemma will be whether they opt to play two spinners or field only one of Ravichandran Ashwin or Ravindra Jadeja. With no Mohammed Shami in the side, the onus will be on Jasprit Bumrah and Mohammed Siraj to deliver and we will see at least if not two out of the three remaining pace options playing in this game. The likes of Rohit Sharma and Virat Kohli will be itching to make their mark and pick up an elusive Test victory in South Africa, at a place that they did win 2021 as well in what might be their final tour to the Rainbow Nation. There's a bit of rain around in Centurion and the forecast for the first two days isn't the brightest but we should in all likelihood get a full game in. Stay tuned as toss and team news are coming up in a bit.

South Africa come into this contest on the back of an average showing in the white-ball format but they do have a solid Test side, one that knows how to win at home. Their star opener and former Test captain Dean Elgar is set to retire at the end of the series and will look to make his marl one last time. The Proteas will be delighted with the fact that both Kagiso Rabada and Lungi Ngidi are available for selection according to the Proteas head coach but we may see a surprise debut for Nandre Burger. The batting will certainly be tested against a very strong Indian bowling lineup and it will be interesting to see whether the hosts can come out on top or not.

Hello and a warm welcome to one and all. It is 'Boxing Day,' a day revered by all sports fans across the globe, and cricket is no exception as South Africa and India gear up to face each other in the 1st Test match of the two-Test series at SuperSport Park in Centurion. The two white-ball series leading up to the big red-ball finale saw both sides field a few familiar and some unknown faces but now both sides will look to field the best team available and get that precious win and points on the WTC table.
... MATCH DAY ...

We are all set for India's second innings. The umpires are out in the middle and so are the players of South Africa who can be seen in a huddle. Skipper, Rohit Sharma and Yashasvi Jaiswal will open the innings for India. Kagiso Rabada has the new ball in hand and is raring to go. Let's play...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

Right then, we are midway through Day 3 and the game has started to move along at a brisk pace. South Africa have piled on the runs on Day 3 and have a solid lead of 163 runs There is still quite on the deck for the seamers and Kagiso Rabada will certainly have his tail up. Can Rohit Sharma and co. put up a stern resistance? We shall find out as India's second innings is up next.

Is Temba Bavuma going to come out or is it all over for South Africa? It's all over and unfortunately, Marco Jansen is left stranded on 84 not out with the lead being 163 runs. Right then, no Temba Bavuma and the South African innings ends on 408 runs. The Proteas did extremely well to pile on quick and big runs in the first session on Day 3 thanks to Dean Elgar's second-highest Test score of 185 and a stellar knock of runs by Marco Jansen down the innings. The pair added on 111 runs for the sixth wicket after which the wickets kept tumbling. They were still able to pick up boundaries every now and then and have done well to end up with a big lead of 163 runs.

India on the other hand will be relieved to finally end the Proteas first innings. They were made to toil long and hard in the field and really didn't have much answer to Dean Elgar and Marco Jansen who really put them under pressure. Jasprit Bumrah though always seemed in the game and after the Lunch interval, he was able to get the job done for his team. Bumrah ended with four wickets and Mohammed Siraj picked up two with all three other bowlers ending with one wicket each. The onus is now on their openers to come out and put up a fight against the new ball.

OUT! BOWLED! That is Jasprit Bumrah's special yorker and through the gates! Bumrah steams in from around the stumps and nails the yorker on off stump. angling it in with good pace behind it as well. That's too good a ball for a tailender and Nandre Burger tries his best to dig it out but the ball sneaks under the bat to castle into the stumps. Bumrah gets his fourth wicket in the inning.

Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the post-Lunch session on Day 3! The umpires and Indian players have taken their places on the field. Marco Jansen and Kagiso Rabada are back to resume their innings. Jasprit Bumrah has the ball in hand and is raring to go.
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

South Africa are 7 down but have extended their lead to a mammoth 147 runs, taking the first session hands-on. Will they keep heaping more runs or will India bundle up the hosts quickly? Join us in the post-Lunch session at 4.40 pm IST (11.10 am GMT) for all the action.

On the bowling front, India initiated with tight lines and lengths from Jasprit Bumrah and Mohammed Siraj. India employed shorter lengths against the hosts which didn't go well. The Proteas then turned the tide, putting India on the defensive as Prasidh Krishna and Shardul Thakur took charge, presenting a stern test for the Indian bowlers. Adding to India's challenges, a few fielding errors crept in too. Even after the new ball was introduced, India found it challenging to stem the flow of runs. Shardul Thakur provided the much-needed breakthrough for India as he got rid of the centurion Dean Elgar, but the damage was already done. Ravichandran Ashwin finally got a wicket right before Lunch but all in all, a disappointing session for the visitors.

Session Summary - 34 overs, 136 runs and 2 wickets! As the players head to Lunch on Day 3, South Africa are surely the happier side of the two, showcasing a fabulous intent in batting. It was a fortunate timely start with the hosts having a slim lead of 11 runs. Dean Elgar and Marco Jansen faced the Indian pacers adeptly, breaking free against Prasidh Krishna and accumulating quick boundaries. Dean Elgar achieved his highest Test score against India and didn't break a sweat, while Marco Jansen displayed a balanced mix of watchfulness and aggression, seizing opportunities with both hands and standing unbeaten on 72, the highest score of his Test career. Dean Elgar was finally dismissed on 185, just 15 short of his 200 right before half an hour or so to Lunch, but he definitely put the hosts in a commanding position. With still no signs of Temba Bavuma, it was Gerald Coetzee who came in to bat. He was aggressive from the moment he came to the crease and struck some powerful boundaries upfront but was soon dismissed by Ashwin in the last over before the Lunch break.
Stays around the wicket to the right-hander as well but Marco Jansen stays solid in defense. This is floated up on middle and leg, Jansen blocks it off the front foot. That will be Lunch on Day 3!

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks break! Well, it has been a listless first 75 minutes or so from India and they are now way behind in this game. Dean Elgar and Marco Jansen have done brilliantly to just get going after a watchful first few overs and now they even look assured against the new ball. They will hope to build on a big lead going into Lunch and set the game up for their pacers later on. Can India pick themselves up and find a way to rip through the Proteas batting line-up? Let's find out.

Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness for the start of play on Day 3! The umpires are out in the middle under the bright sunshine and so are the Indian players. Dean Elgar and Marco Jansen are all set to resume their overnight stay on the crease. Jasprit Bumrah to begin proceedings with the ball. Let's go...

PITCH REPORT - Shaun Pollock and Ravi Shastri are down for the pitch report. Pollock says that it will help the pacers a lot as the sun is out and it's shining bright. The overcast conditions have helped the pitch to hold up and also it's rolled in nicely. Ravi Shastri then adds that it might deteriorate as the day progresses and a variable bounce might come into play during the evening. He adds that batting will get a bit more tougher and challenging as there are a few patches and a minimal rough around and the ball will do a bit of mischief as well.

Indian wicket-keeper and the centurion from the first innings, KL Rahul is down for a chat. He says it's a crucial stage of the game and is very important for India to play well, bowling in the right areas and getting the key wicket of Dean Elgar. He adds that the wicket was challenging in the first innings given that it was under the covers for a couple of days, and the great bowling effort from the Proteas ensured we did not get off to a great start. He further says he was trying to take his chances and score as many as possible with the tail-enders. He concludes that it's his first game, batting in the middle order and keeping wickets, so it has been challenging and he looks forward to it.

India on the other hand will be a tad disappointed with how they bowled and a few of their tactics with the ball were questionable. Jasprit Bumrah though looked on song and so did Mohammed Siraj but he lacked a bit of consistency. Shardul Thakur struggled to find his rhythm and bowled quite a few No Balls as well while debutant Prasidh Krishna seemed under pressure until that burst right before play was called off on Day 2. Ravichandran Ashwin has been underutilized so far but we might see a bit more of him if there are cracks. However, given that there is sunshine, the pitch might quicken up and the pacers might enjoy bowling more. With play scheduled to start on time, the first session is set up to be a crucial one. Stick around for further updates.

South Africa had a stellar Day 2 but would have been quite content to see the play being called off due to bad light as they were just starting to get a bit fidgety under testing conditions. Dean Elgar, in his farewell series, has played what could be his best Test knock ever and we have never seen him attack the way he did, hitting 23 fours so far in his knock of 140 runs and he will have one eye on that elusive double ton but it won't be easy. The big question still remains though - whether skipper Temba Bavuma will come out to bat or not? If he does, the Proteas will be very pleased and if he doesn't then Elgar will be looking to add quick runs in the first session to take the lead around the 100-run mark.

Hello and welcome back to the SuperSport Park in Centurion for our coverage of Day 3 of the 1st Test match between South Africa and India. We have had two days marred with delayed starts and early finishes but thankfully, the sun is out in Centurion and the forecast for the day looks good. Day 2 belonged to Dean Elgar and the hosts who were able to build up a lead of 11 runs before play got abandoned due to bad light and still have five wickets in hand. India are currently behind the eight ball and need a big first hour on Day 3 to make their way back into the game.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, two days of Test cricket have gone by and we haven't quite seen a full day's worth of play, actually far from it. Day 3 is generally known as the moving day in Test cricket, so, let's hope we get a nice, sunny morning on Thursday and play can commence on time. South Africa have the lead and are in pole position to build on it as well but it will be interesting to see how the Indian pacers go about their business early on Day 3. Once again play might begin half an hour earlier than the scheduled 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT) start weather permitting that is but you can join us a lot earlier for the build-up. Cheers!

India started the day positively and have ended it positively as well but between all that, they were second best. After KL Rahul's second ton in Centurion, the Indian pace duo of Jasprit Bumrah and Mohammed Siraj started off pretty well and Siraj even picked up an early wicket. However, the likes of Shardul Thakur and debutant Prasidh Krishna couldn't bowl consistent lines and lengths and conceded way too many runs. Bumrah did strike twice in his second spell but once again, India let it slip. In the last hour or so of play on Day 2, Prasidh Krishna and Mohammed Siraj bent their backs and bowled a few feisty short balls with the odd fuller one in between and that got them a couple of breakthroughs as well. India couldn't build on it much as the light faded and the players had to go off the field.

There it is, play has officially been called off on Day 2! End of another fascinating day of Test cricket which started with KL Rahul really irritating the Proteas and ended with Dean Elgar standing tall for his side as South Africa carved out a 11-run lead with five wickets still in hand. South Africa will certainly be pleased heading into the dressing room as they have been able to make Day 2 their own. They seemed to have leaked a few too many runs early with the ball and even lost Aiden Markram quite early on but the stand-in skipper, Dean Elgar has played a sensational knock and is still unbeaten on 140 runs after scoring his first century on his home ground which incidentally is also his last home Test match. Apart from him, Tony de Zorzi showed good technique up top and it was really the stand between Elgar and debutant David Bedingham worth 131 runs that really turned the tide in South Africa's favor. Bedingham who made his Test debut after more than 80 first-class matches and 18 first-class tons to his name, made a fine fifty before getting out. They will now look to come out on Day 3 and pile on early runs in the first session to sink India further.

A slight halt in play as Dean Elgar seems to have taken a blow to his left hand. Oh, wait! The bails are taken off and the players are walking off the field due to bad light. Play hasn't been called off yet but given the light is getting bleaker by the minute, this might be it for Day 2. Stay tuned as we bring you further updates.

Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the final session on Day 2! About 38 overs are left in the day's play but that will in all likelihood not be achieved. The umpires are back out in the middle and so are the Indian players who are standing around the boundary ropes and can be seen in a huddle where Virat Kohli is seen having a few words of wisdom, no Rohit Sharma on the field of play, strange. Dean Elgar and David Bedingham are all set to resume their stay on the crease as well. It will be Jasprit Bumrah who will start proceedings with the ball post the Tea break. Let's play...
... DAY 2, SESSION 3 ...

With South Africa trailing by just 51 runs, the final session of Day 2 will prove pivotal in shaping the test match. Will India make a comeback and restrict the Proteas from getting away with a huge lead? Or will the Proteas continue to annoy the Indians? Let's wait and watch as the final session of Day 2 will come to you shortly.

South Africa on the other hand will be mighty pleased by their overall performance which started extremely well right from the first hour of play in the session. After the early wicket of Aiden Markram, Dean Elgar and Tony de Zorzi built a solid partnership of 93 runs that put the Proteas right in the front. The duo stepped on the gas right after lunch scoring at a healthy rate before Jasprit applied the break to their partnership by claiming Zorzi's wicket. The veteran star, Dean Elgar has once again proved his class and temperament for his undefeated knock of 115 runs along with David Bedingham who has impressed the cricketing world on his debut mustering up 32 runs in just 47 balls.

Session Summary - 33 overs, 145 runs and 2 wickets! Another well-fought session but at the end of it, South Africa are firmly in command as they trail by just 51 runs and have 7 wickets in hand to go along with two set-batters at the crease. The Indians might have missed a trick at the start of the session, by not starting off with the prime bowlers to ball from both ends. Both Prasidh Krishna and Shardul Thakur struggled with their lines and lengths leaking away just too many runs in that opening spell. 42 runs were added quickly before captain Rohit Sharma decided to bring back Jasprit Bumrah who proved lethal by knocking off the set batter Tony de Zorzi followed by Keegan Peterson in quick succession. Since then though, the hosts have once again been able to build a steady stand and negate the Indian bowlers.
One more bumper to end and that will be Tea on Day 2! This is banged in halfway down the pitch and over the stumps, Dean Elgar ducks under it well.

Commentary.Commentary: We are all set for the start of the post-Lunch session on Day 2! The umpires are out in the middle and the Indian players have taken their places on the field. Dean Elgar and Tony de Zorzi are ready to resume their innings. It will be Shardul Thakur to begin proceedings with the ball after the interval.
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

Right then, South Africa will look forward to piling up runs without losing many wickets and narrowing the lead on this tricky track to bat, whereas, India would be batting an eye to take wickets as early as possible. It will be crucial to see how the Proteas negotiate with the Indian bowling line-up. A riveting session 2 awaits us. Join us for the post-Lunch session at 4.40 pm IST (11.10 am GMT).

South African openers Aiden Markram and Dean Elgar began the innings for the Proteas. They were tentative and watchful as the new ball was doing a bit of mischief early on. Aiden Markram was the first and only man to fall for the Proteas. Following an early dismissal, Tony de Zorzi and Dean Elgar somehow managed to stick to the crease till the Lunch and the Proteas scored 49 till the end of the session. India on the other hand broke the shackles early on as Mohammed Siraj dismissed Aiden Markram cheaply within half an hour time frame. Jasprit Bumrah kept the pressure ticking on the hosts as he bowled a tidy brilliant spell with tight lines and lengths. Prasidh Krishna, the debutant for India, was introduced sooner and was taken on by Elgar in his two overs so far.

This brings us to the end of the first session of Day 2 as the players head for Lunch. Identical to the first day, the play initiated with a slight delay due to rain, a wet outfield and seemingly overcast conditions. It was a quick burst of half an hour or so that saw KL Rahul notch up his 8th Test ton and South Africa were able to bundle out India after some stern resistance. Since then though, South Africa have managed the early barrage from the Indian bowlers well and will be delighted to go into the break with just one wicket down for 49 runs.

A maiden to end the session but Tony de Zorzi negotiated the final over really well. Another one that is bowled a bit fuller and slower, drifting into the stumps, de Zorzi keeps it out. That will be Lunch on Day 2!

Commentary.Commentary: Right then, given that this is only a two-match Test series, India have yet again failed to conquer that elusive first Test series win in South Africa which is also considered as the 'final frontier' for India. On the other hand, the Proteas have once again shown why they have been such a class red-ball outfit over the last two decades or so even with what looked like a slightly depleted and inexperienced lineup. The curtain comes down on the year 2023 as these two sides will now meet in the 2nd Test and the final match of this tour in 2024. The 2nd Test will be played at Newlands in Cape Town and will begin on the 3rd of January at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT). However, you can join us a lot sooner for the build-up. Till then, take care and we wish everyone a Happy New Year. Cheers!

Dean Elgar, the stand-in captain for South Africa is also the Player of the match for his sublime knock of 185 runs in the first innings. He says that it's pretty special for him and gets emotional and says that he's gonna cry but will smile and enjoy the moment. Adds that contributing to the team is the main focus and the guys did well collectively as a group. It was a massive effort. Says that the wicket was quite juicy and that they planned to simplify everything without trying anything extra. Adds that a few good partnerships with Tony de Zorzi, David Bedingham and Marco Jansen really paved the way for them to get that broad lead ahead of the Indians. He appreciates David Bedingham for his phenomenal contribution on debut. He says that they needed no less than 20 wickets to get a win against such a talented Indian side. He goes on to say that Kagiso Rabada and Nandre Burger bowled amazing spells, especially Burger who shined on his debut and got the reward. In the end, he thanks the crowd and concludes by saying that he's leaving on a good positive note.

Rohit Sharma, the Indian captain, says he is disappointed and feels they were not good enough to win this Test match. He adds that they batted decently in the first innings but fell short after that. He then says that every individual in the team has their own plans in place and knows what is expected out of them. He makes a note of the hard lines and lengths that the Proteas bowled which was crucial and they failed to negate it well. He also appreciates KL Rahul's knock in the first innings along with the batting performance from Virat Kohli. He further concludes that it is important for the team to regroup and get out of this loss and focus on the next one ahead of them.
The Presentation ceremony...

A marvelous inning from Virat Kohli goes in vain as only two batters get into double-figures for India in their second innings and they have bundled out for a meager score of 131 runs. It was an ominous start as skipper Rohit Sharma fell prey to Kagiso Rabada for a duck and his opening partner soon followed. Shubman Gill looked fairly settled and played some delightful shots alongside Kohli but got out and after that the middle order simply crumbled. Kohli saw that he was running out of partners and tried to muster up as many runs as possible but it was by no means enough. With the ball, Jasprit Bumrah looked like the only one who had a clear assessment of the track and even though Mohammed Siraj bowled well in patches, the other two seamers were simply off their game. KL Rahul was the only other batter apart from Kohli who actually showed grit in the first innings and along with the tail gave India half a chance in the first innings. Overall though, this was an unexpected result, one which should come as a wake-up call to the visitors.

Coming into Day 3, the Proteas were well ahead of the game having a triple-digit lead under their belt and they quickly added vital runs to take it to 163 runs before getting bundled out with a man short. Marco Jansen didn't have a say with the ball in the first innings but he certainly made and impact with the bat with a career-best 84 not out and was able to take that form into his bowling in the second innings as he picked up three big wickets. Kagiso Rabada and Nandre Burger though were the ones who did most of the damage in both innings and ended with 7 wickets each in the game. Burger just looks the part and in him, South Africa might have found a talented and aggressive left-arm pacer for the next few years. All in all, Dean Elgar dominated with the bat and in general they dominated with ball in hand as well and have taken an unassailable 1-0 lead in the two-Test series.

What an end to the 1st Test match and what a memorable one it has been for the hometown boy - Dean Elgar who leads his side to a wonderful win. There are tears in his eyes as he knows it is the last time he has played at this ground but South Africa have dominated the game against a few odds too. There was an injury cloud hovering over the likes of Kagiso Rabada and Lungi Ngidi but the former did play and was one of the chief architects of the win as well. In the absence of skipper Temba Bavuma who injured his hamstring on Day 1 itself, the others stepped up and even the two debutants - Nandre Burger and David Bedingham played vital roles in the win. As for India, it was yet again a case of relying on individual brilliance rather than playing together as a team and providing support to each other and they have suffered a huge innings defeat.

OUT! TAKEN! Wow, what a catch to end it all and fittingly it is Kagiso Rabada who takes it. Marco Jansen comes in from around the stumps and digs it in short over the stumps. Virat Kohli dances down the track and flat-bats it up and over the bowler's head without great timing. KG races across to his left from long on and takes a fine tumbling catch on the run with both hands. Jansen ends with a third wicket and the Proteas are absolutely pumped up. SOUTH AFRICA WIN BY AN INNINGS AND 32 RUNS!

South Africa do take the review and why not with just two wickets remaining. The physio comes out but UltraEdge shows that the ball went off the right thumb before it took the helmet and Burger has his fourth wicket.

OUT! EDGED AND GONE! Nandre Burger comes back into the attack and picks up a massive wicket for South Africa. Burger goes wider on the crease and angles in a fuller delivery close to the off stump. The ball goes quickly around chest height to Aiden Markram at second slip and this time he makes no mistake. India have lost half their side now and they still trail by 67 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness for the final session on Day 3! The umpires and the players of South Africa are back out in the middle. The duo of Virat Kohli and Shreyas Iyer are all set to resume their stay on the crease. It will be Gerald Coetzee to get proceedings underway with the ball. Let's go...
... DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

With still 101 runs needed to level scores, will the Proteas be able to go for the kill and dent the Indian batting lineup? Or will Virat Kohli and Shreyas Iyer resurrect the innings and put on a great partnership? Let's wait and watch as the final session of the day comes to you shortly.

The Proteas did great to add a lead of 163 runs on the board with a batter short. Marco Jansen was unfortunately left stranded at one end scoring an unbeaten 84 runs. The two pacers up top, Kagiso Rabada and Nandre Burger bowled fiery spells right from the go and ensured at no point in time India got into the game. A couple of missed chances at the slips will hurt the Proteas a bit but the way they have kept piling the pressure on the Indians will make up for it.

Another session of Test cricket comes to an end and at the end of the second session on Day 3, India are 62/3, trailing South Africa by 101 more runs. Jasprit Bumrah started off the post-Lunch session bowling hard lines and lengths and knocked KG in the very first over followed by Nandre Burger to finish the innings for the Proteas. After a great start to the Session with the ball, India was taken aback with both the openers being dismissed early in the innings. Shubnam Gill and Virat Kohli did steady the nerves a bit and fought back well to get India out of the hole but the wicket of Shubman Gill a few minutes before Tea further added to their misery.
Back of a length, angling in from outside off, Shreyas Iyer negates the ball well as that one stayed low. That will be Tea on Day 3!

Commentary.Commentary: Virat Kohli walks in at number 4 with his side in a spot of bother.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Brilliant from Nandre Burger and he picks off Yashasvi Jaiswal yet again and India are in early trouble here. Burger bangs it in a bit on a tighter line around off stump, angling it in. Jaiswal watches it well and looks to shoulder arms but the steep bounce means he cannot get those gloves high enough. The ball just kisses the under-glove and goes through to Kyle Verreynne who makes no error. Jaiswal departs for a low score on his birthday and India still trail by 150 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Kyle Verreynne b Nandre Burger
Commentary.Default_Commentary: 5.3: Nandre Burger to Yashasvi Jaiswal, OUT! c Kyle Verreynne b Nandre Burger.

OUT! TIMBER! Kagiso Rabada with a special delivery and he keeps tormenting Rohit Sharma. Rabada steams in and pitches it up on middle stump with the angle into the right-hander. The ball pitches and nips away sharply as Sharma plays completely down the wrong line and is beaten past the outside edge. The ball knocks over the off stump and Rabada sends Sharma packing for a duck and for a seventh time in 11 innings as well. Perfect start for South Africa here.
Commentary.Howout: b Kagiso Rabada
Commentary.Default_Commentary: 2.5: Kagiso Rabada to Rohit Sharma, OUT! b Kagiso Rabada.
